    body: `
      <p>Working remotely from Rome is one of the greatest perks of the digital nomad life, but here's the challenge: your apartment might be charming, but it might also have WiFi that cuts out during important calls, interruptions, and the general distractions of living in one of the world's most vibrant cities. That's where coworking spaces come in—they're sanctuaries for focus, hubs for networking, and often genuinely welcoming communities that prevent remote work isolation.</p>

      <h2>Why Coworking Matters More Than You'd Think</h2>

      <p>Working only from home in Rome can be amazing, but it can also feel isolating. Coworking spaces are where you'll meet other remote workers, potential collaborators, and genuinely interesting people building things. Plus, the separation between "home" and "work" becomes crucial for mental health when both happen in the same apartment.</p>

      <h2>Top Coworking Spaces in Rome</h2>

      <p><strong>ImpactHub Roma (Testaccio)</strong></p>
      <p>This is the premium choice for mission-driven workers. Located in Testaccio near the vibrant food scene, ImpactHub focuses on social entrepreneurs and impact-driven projects. The community is genuinely engaged—you'll find founders, consultants, and creatives. They host regular events, mentoring sessions, and workshops. WiFi is rock-solid. The space is beautiful, with both open desks and quiet zones. Membership runs €250-400/month depending on your plan. If you care about being around people building meaningful stuff, this is the place.</p>

      <p><strong>We-Work-Nomads (Monti/multiple locations)</strong></p>
      <p>Specifically geared toward remote workers and digital nomads, We-Work-Nomads has multiple locations across Rome and maintains excellent standards. The community is international and genuinely friendly. WiFi is tested and verified reliable—critical for nomads. Hot desks start around €150/month; private desks slightly more. They organize social events and language exchanges. The Monti location is particularly vibrant.</p>

      <p><strong>Arché Coworking (Trastevere)</strong></p>
      <p>Smaller and more intimate than other options, Arché is beloved by many expats for its genuine, welcoming atmosphere. Less corporate, more artisanal. Good for people who find massive open-plan spaces overwhelming. They have both individual desks and private studios. Cost is around €180-300/month. The neighborhood is perfect—walk out to amazing restaurants and bars.</p>

      <p><strong>Remix Coworking (Ostiense)</strong></p>
      <p>In the trendy Ostiense neighborhood, Remix is more affordable (€120-200/month) while maintaining solid standards. It's less touristy than Trastevere or Monti, which appeals to many expats seeking "real Rome" while staying productive. The space is industrial-chic with good energy. Growing community of tech workers and creators.</p>

      <p><strong>WeWork (Piazza di Spagna)</strong></p>
      <p>If you prefer the corporate infrastructure of an international chain, WeWork in Rome's central location offers all the amenities you'd expect. WiFi is enterprise-grade, facilities are top-tier, but it's pricier (€400-700/month) and less community-oriented. Good if you need serious infrastructure and don't mind paying for polish.</p>

      <h2>Budget Options and Alternatives</h2>

      <p>Not everyone can afford €250+/month on coworking. Rome has options:</p>

      <p><strong>Temporary Day Passes:</strong> Most coworking spaces offer day passes (€15-25) if you want to test the space or work occasionally. This is smart—try before you buy a membership.</p>

      <p><strong>Cafés with Attitude:</strong> Rome has countless cafés where remote workers gather. Maison Mangostan, Armando al Pantheon (has a back room area), and various spots in Trastevere are legitimately work-friendly. Order a coffee, work for hours, nobody minds. Cost: €3-5 for your caffeine commitment.</p>

      <p><strong>Library Access:</strong> The Biblioteca di Roma has study areas and WiFi. It's quiet, academic, and free with registration. Not ideal for video calls, but great for focused solo work.</p>

      <p><strong>University Spaces:</strong> If you have connections at a university (teaching, studying, etc.), campus spaces are often open to community members. Ask around.</p>

      <h2>What to Look For in a Coworking Space</h2>

      <p><strong>Internet Speed:</strong> This is non-negotiable. Any provider worth your money tests speeds and guarantees minimum bandwidth. Ask them to run a speed test during your trial day. You need minimum 10Mbps download, ideally more.</p>

      <p><strong>Backup Power:</strong> Italy's grid is reliable, but occasional outages happen. Does the space have backup generators or UPS systems? For remote workers, this can be critical.</p>

      <p><strong>Phone Booths/Quiet Spaces:</strong> If you take video calls, you need isolated spaces. Open-plan offices are great for energy but terrible for meetings. Best spaces have multiple phone booths or quiet areas.</p>

      <p><strong>Community Events:</strong> Are they hosting talks, workshops, or social events? This is where coworking becomes transformative rather than just a place to sit.</p>

      <p><strong>Kitchen and Facilities:</strong> You're going to spend 40+ hours here monthly. Decent kitchen, bathroom quality, and seating variety matter more than you'd expect.</p>

      <h2>The Social Dimension</h2>

      <p>Here's something nobody tells you: coworking spaces in Rome are where you'll make your first genuine friendships with other expats. You're around the same people regularly, working on often-similar challenges, and there's built-in conversation starters. I've seen professional collaborations, romantic relationships, and lifelong friendships start in these spaces.</p>

      <p>The best spaces deliberately build community. They host after-work drinks, organize skill-share sessions, and create slacks/group chats. Pay attention to community during your trial day. If people are actually talking and organizing things, that's worth premium pricing. If it's just people sitting silently, it's just an expensive café.</p>

      <h2>Making the Decision</h2>

      <p>Most coworking spaces offer trial days. Use them. Spend a full day working there. Test the WiFi during different times. Talk to other members. See if you feel like you belong. Your workspace affects your productivity, mood, and social life more than you'd expect.</p>

      <p>Budget-wise, if you can afford it, choose based on community fit rather than cost. €250-400/month is not that much when you consider improved productivity, mental health, and the relationships you'll build. But if you're on a tighter budget, you absolutely can work from cafés and occasional shared spaces.</p>

      <p><em>Rome's coworking spaces await. Find yours and build something great.</em></p>
    `
